Step 1: Create a Project Directory
mkdir java-docker-addition
cd java-docker-addition

Step 2: Create the Java Program
nano Addition.java
Paste this code:
.....
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Addition {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

        System.out.print("Enter first number: ");
        int num1 = sc.nextInt();

        System.out.print("Enter second number: ");
        int num2 = sc.nextInt();

        int sum = num1 + num2;

        System.out.println("The sum of " + num1 + " and " + num2 + " is: " + sum);
        sc.close();
    }
}

....

Step 3: Create the Dockerfile
nano Dockerfile
Paste the following:
....
# Step 1: Use official OpenJDK base image
FROM openjdk:17-jdk-slim

# Step 2: Set the working directory inside the container
WORKDIR /app

# Step 3: Copy the Java file into the container
COPY Addition.java /app

# Step 4: Compile the Java program
RUN javac Addition.java

# Step 5: Run the compiled Java program
CMD ["java", "Addition"]
....

Step 4: Build the Docker Image
Run the following command in the same directory:
docker build -t addition-java .

Step 5: Run the Docker Container
docker run -it addition-java

Step 6 (Optional): Push to Docker Hub
If you want to make your image publicly available:
docker tag addition-java <your-dockerhub-username>/addition-java:latest
docker push <your-dockerhub-username>/addition-java:latest
Then anyone can run it using:
docker run -it <your-dockerhub-username>/addition-java:latest

docker run -it <your-dockerhub-username>/addition-java:latest
